While observing PET through PL-based measurements, some of the transient intermediates formed during the process may get undetected due to their non-fluorescent characteristics (quenched or dark states) and ultrashort lifetimes (beyond the detection limit of the instrument). This makes it difficult to ascertain and track the underlying photoinduced reaction pathways. T-T transient absorption measurements often come to the rescue in such situations, as the transients in the T states often have a prolonged lifetime (sub μs to ms) compared to their S states. Recent exploration in long-lived T state exciton dynamics like T-T annihilation, S-T annihilation, and thermally activated delayed fluorescence have been successfully manipulated to increase the internal quantum efficiency of organic light-emitting diodes [44]. Here, we wish to track any non-fluorescent transient formed between the CDs and MQ and follow the sequence of events after photoexcitation through T-T absorption. Fig. 3
                         (3a-orange and 3b-dark cyan) shows typical T-T absorption spectra of CDs for homogeneous water and the confined Brij-35 media respectively. The spectra reflect two separate transition states with two distinct features at 370 nm (peak-I) and a broad absorption around 400–500 nm (peak-II) in both media [26]. Our observed spectra are in good agreement with previous literature reports on the T-T absorption of CDs [24,28]. While peak-I is less prominent in the water medium, the transition becomes more distinct with the Brij-35 medium. Peak I has been ascribed to the higher energy transition due to the T state (π -π*), while the broader Peak II can be assigned to the T state (n -π*). With the gradual addition of MQ (0.5 mM (pink) and 1 mM (violet)) (Fig. 3), we observe a sequential increment in the absorption around 380 nm for water, while an overall increase for both the peaks is observed in Brij-35 medium. In presence of the MQ, the peak I around 370 nm is found to be relatively narrow for water compared to Brij-35, which reflects a broad feature extending beyond 420 nm. For peak II, we hardly observe any change in the absorption of water, however, a significant increment in the peak is observed for Brij-35 for a very broader range. The observations of T-T spectra for the aqueous and neutral Brij-35 medium hint at two different modes of interactions of CDs with MQ in the homogeneous and micro-heterogeneous media. An earlier report suggests that the quinones have much faster ISC rates with higher triplet quantum yield with strong absorption around the 360–370 nm range [45]. This is evident with a sharp absorption around the 360–370 nm range for both media, indicating the presence of triplet-MQ (3MQ) states. Along with the 3MQ, we detect the electron transport product MQ●- in the region near 420 nm, as reported in earlier literature [46,47]. Control measurement of the triplet states of the MQ-only sample is shown in Fig. S4, with distinct features of 3MQ and 3MQ●-. This peak appears more prominent for the Brij-35 micelles compared to the aqueous medium. This shows that the PET becomes more facile in the heterogeneous micellar environment (Scheme 1
                        ). Micelles have been reported to encapsulate small molecules inside the hydrophobic core, creating a host–guest type structure and helping in regulating the random diffusion of the reacting molecules [43,48]. The MQ undergoes one or two-electron reduction in presence of a donor entity to yield unstable semiquinone facilitating the CT process [49,50]. MQ being small is encapsulated in the micellar cage forming encounter complex with CDs, hence can undergo photo-induced interaction with ease. On the contrary, inside the homogeneous aqueous media, the molecules can diffuse very rapidly with a very low probability of collisional encounters with each other.
